@page "/help"
@attribute [Authorize]

<PageTitle>AiPulse · Help</PageTitle>

<div class="page-header">
    <h1><Icon Name="help-circle" Size="22" /> Help &amp; Getting Started</h1>
    <p class="lead">What AiPulse is, what every page does, and how to actually use it day to day.</p>
</div>

<div class="card mb-4">
    <div class="card-body">
        <h4 class="section-title"><Icon Name="zap" /> What is this?</h4>
        <p>
            AiPulse is your personal, self-hosted station for keeping up with AI news and leveling up as a developer.
            It pulls live updates from ~40 sources (blogs, research feeds, GitHub releases, YouTube, Reddit, Mastodon…),
            and pairs that feed with a curated glossary, a tools comparison, and a learning roadmap — all in one place,
            so you don't have to piece it together from a dozen tabs.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-0">
            <strong>It runs standalone — no AI, no API key, nothing to configure to get value from it.</strong>
            Everything you see (aggregation, tagging, summaries, digest) is plain code: HTTP fetches, XML parsing,
            keyword matching. There's an optional AI hook for later, but it's off by default and nothing here needs it.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="alert alert-light border mb-4">
    <h6 class="section-title"><Icon Name="sparkle" Size="16" /> New install? A few things are supposed to look empty at first</h6>
    <p class="mb-1">
        The News Feed itself is live from the first visit, but a few things only build up the longer AiPulse
        keeps running — none of this is broken, it just needs time:
    </p>
    <ul class="mb-0 small">
        <li>The Dashboard's <strong>Trending panel</strong> and <strong>Activity heatmap</strong> start nearly empty and fill in day by day.</li>
        <li>The <strong>Weekly Digest</strong>'s "biggest stories" needs several days of coverage to say anything meaningful.</li>
        <li><strong>Source health (Uptime 30d)</strong> on the Sources page shows "no data yet" until at least one day has been recorded.</li>
        <li><strong>Notifications</strong> deliberately stay quiet on the very first check so you're not flooded with the entire backlog as "new" — see below.</li>
        <li>The Dashboard's <strong>"New since last visit"</strong> count will look unusually large on your very first visit, since there's no prior visit to compare against yet.</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h4 class="section-title"><Icon Name="rss" /> A typical day</h4>
<ol class="mb-4">
    <li class="mb-2"><strong>Open the <a href="">Dashboard</a>.</strong> It shows what's trending this week, your activity timeline, and where you left off in the Learning Hub.</li>
    <li class="mb-2"><strong>Check the <a href="news">News Feed</a>.</strong> Filter to <span class="badge bg-danger">New</span> to see only what's arrived since your last visit. Save anything worth a deeper read by clicking the 🏷️ tag icon — it goes to your <a href="bookmarks">Reading List</a>.</li>
    <li class="mb-2"><strong>Missed a few days?</strong> Open the <a href="digest">Weekly Digest</a> instead — a 7-day rollup of the biggest stories and what's trending, rather than scrolling everything individually.</li>
    <li class="mb-2"><strong>Heard a term you didn't recognize?</strong> Search it in the <a href="glossary">Glossary</a> — it's written for developers, not textbooks, and includes slang/mis-heard versions (e.g. searching "headroom" finds "context headroom").</li>
    <li class="mb-2"><strong>Starting a coding task?</strong> Check <a href="tools">Tools &amp; Tips</a> for which AI tool actually fits the job, plus concrete token-saving moves.</li>
    <li><strong>Want to learn something end-to-end?</strong> Work through the <a href="learn">Learning Hub</a> roadmap — it's ordered from fundamentals to agents, each module says <em>why</em> it matters, not just what to read.</li>
</ol>

